# DSNConfigurator maps smtps:// to STARTTLS instead of implicit TLS

## Summary

`DSNConfigurator` currently maps the `smtps://` scheme to `PHPMailer::ENCRYPTION_STARTTLS`, while also defaulting the port to `SMTP::DEFAULT_SECURE_PORT` (465).

This seems inconsistent with the conventional meaning of `smtps://`, which is implicit TLS: the TLS handshake should happen before any SMTP protocol bytes are sent. STARTTLS is explicit TLS and is normally represented by SMTP on port 587 or an explicit `tls`/STARTTLS setting.

## Current Behavior

In `src/DSNConfigurator.php`, `configureSMTP()` does this:

```php
$isSMTPS = 'smtps' === $config['scheme'];

if ($isSMTPS) {
    $mailer->SMTPSecure = PHPMailer::ENCRYPTION_STARTTLS;
}
```

If no port is specified, it then uses `SMTP::DEFAULT_SECURE_PORT`:

```php
} elseif ($isSMTPS) {
    $mailer->Port = SMTP::DEFAULT_SECURE_PORT;
}
```

The tests also assert this behavior:

```php
$configurator->configure($this->Mail, 'smtps://user:pass@remotehost');
self::assertEquals($this->Mail->SMTPSecure, PHPMailer::ENCRYPTION_STARTTLS);
self::assertEquals($this->Mail->Port, SMTP::DEFAULT_SECURE_PORT);
```

## Expected Behavior

I would expect:

```text
smtps://user:pass@example.com
```

to configure:

```php
$mailer->SMTPSecure = PHPMailer::ENCRYPTION_SMTPS;
$mailer->Port = SMTP::DEFAULT_SECURE_PORT;
```

That would match the usual semantics of `smtps://` and align with the README example for port 465:

```php
$mail->SMTPSecure = PHPMailer::ENCRYPTION_SMTPS;
$mail->Port = 465;
```

## Why This Matters

With the current mapping, a DSN that appears to request implicit TLS instead configures explicit STARTTLS on the implicit TLS port. That can cause interoperability problems with strict SMTPS servers and may surprise users who expect `smtps://` to mean TLS from connection start.

## Suggested Fix

Change the `smtps://` branch to:

```php
if ($isSMTPS) {
    $mailer->SMTPSecure = PHPMailer::ENCRYPTION_SMTPS;
}
```

and update the DSNConfigurator tests accordingly.

I am happy to open a PR if this behavior is considered unintentional.

