# Problem description
I have a process that sends out two emails. The first email was sent successfully. The second email fails with the following error:

Cannot declare class PHPMailer\PHPMailer\PHPMailer, because the name is already in use
libraries/php-mailer/PHPMailer.php
Line 32: "class PHPMailer"

So I have a PHP includes file with a function that translates my code to work with PHPMailer and then return the result to the calling function:

```
 if (!function_exists('smtp_phpmailer'))
 {
  include($includes.'functions_phpmailer.php');
 }
```

I don't do classes so this is all on the documentation. Apparently classes can't be declared within functions, fine, I declare it before the function. However I attempted to address this issue directly myself however this didn't resolve the problem:

```
if (!class_exists('PHPMailer\PHPMailer\PHPMailer'))
{
 use PHPMailer\PHPMailer\PHPMailer;
 use PHPMailer\PHPMailer\SMTP;
 use PHPMailer\PHPMailer\Exception;
}
```

So I removed the if condition. Apparently also use PHPMailer\PHPMailer\SMTP; is no longer needed? That brings me to the next obvious point: I updated to a stable build from November 2025 build to the latest stable build.

I never figured out the purpose of classes so I've avoided them as they just make code convoluted. I'm not sure how else to address this issue. I haven't changed any code, the only thing that changed was the server. The new host uses an earlier iteration of PHP 8.3 as I'm still iterating over the php.ini configuration file (everything _is_ up to date though). I'll post it in a little while after I remove all of the commentary. I'm 99% certain it's a configuration issue.

Again, the first email gets sent just fine. [mail-tester](https://www.mail-tester.com/) is still giving me a 10/10 (thank you _very much_ for that!) so again, I'm 99% certain it's a server configuration that is causing the problem. I'll post it as soon as I've removed all of the comments. Also, would a debug output really be useful here? I can include that if desired.

